  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different jurisdictions:\n\n1. United States\n- Comprehensive Anti-Money Laundering (AML) regulations\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Strict reporting requirements\n- Significant criminal and civil penalties\n- Extensive regulatory oversight\n\n2. European Union\n- Unified regulatory framework\n- Directive on preventing money laundering\n- Centralized reporting mechanisms\n- Harmonized legal standards across member states\n- Strong emphasis on financial transparency\n\n3. United Kingdom\n- Sophisticated legal framework\n- Proceeds of Crime Act\n- Enhanced due diligence requirements\n- Robust financial intelligence unit\n- Proactive international cooperation\n\n4. Switzerland\n- Historically lenient banking regulations\n- Gradually increasing transparency\n- Strong financial privacy laws\n- Developing stricter international compliance standards\n\n5. Singapore\n- Strict regulatory environment\n- Advanced technological monitoring\n- Comprehensive legal framework\n- Significant penalties for non-compliance\n\n6. China\n- Increasing regulatory complexity\n- Centralized enforcement mechanisms\n- Growing international cooperation\n- Developing sophisticated detection systems\n\nThese approaches vary in strictness, implementation, and specific legal mechanisms.",
